# Quality Gate

- **Clean Code (Uncle Bob)**: Write code following principles from *Clean Code* by Robert C. Martin: meaningful names, small functions, single responsibility, minimal comments (code explains itself), no duplication, clear abstractions, low coupling, and tests that are clean too.
- **Use Makefile commands only**: Never run `pnpm`, `docker compose exec`, or similar directly. Use `make dev`, `make build`, `make lint`, `make test`, `make add PKG=...`, `make add-dev PKG=...`, etc.
- **Validate before finishing**: After any code change, run `make quality-gate`. This runs **build**, **lint**, and **unit tests** (`make test`) in sequence. All must exit with code 0 and report zero errors.
- **TDD on bug fixes (when requested or clearly a regression)**: Prefer the workflow in `.cursor/skills/tdd-bugfix/SKILL.md`: add or adjust a **failing test** that encodes the correct behavior (optionally after temporarily reverting an existing fix to get a red run), apply the **minimal fix**, then run **`make quality-gate`**. Link new tests to OpenSpec tasks only when that change lives under an active OpenSpec change and it helps traceability.
- **Linter must be flawless**: ESLint must report 0 problems. Fix any errors or warnings before considering work complete.
- **Unit tests are the main safety net**: Prefer thorough Vitest coverage on **changed code paths**—edge cases, regressions, services, hooks, and UI behavior you can assert without a browser—so preventable bugs surface in unit tests instead of first failing in CI Playwright runs.
- **When to run E2E locally**: GitHub CI runs **`make e2e-test`** on pull requests. Run **`make e2e-test`** locally when you touch routing, auth, or other flows covered by Playwright, or when debugging a CI e2e failure—not as part of every small edit.
- **Build must succeed**: TypeScript compilation and Vite build must complete with no errors or warnings.
- **Shop schema / Sheets layout**: If you change `SHEET_HEADERS`, `validateStructure`, shop metadata shape, or sheet migrations, bump **`src/config/version.ts`** (patch at minimum; **major** when `validateShopFolder` must reject old shops until they are migrated).
- **OpenSpec changes stay out of git**: The directory `openspec/changes/` is listed in `.gitignore`. Do not `git add` OpenSpec change folders unless the user explicitly asks to track them (e.g. `git add -f`). Agents must not instruct committing those paths by default.
- **Check for unarchived changes before committing**: Before creating a git commit, run `openspec list --json`. If there are active (non-archived) changes, warn the user and ask for confirmation before proceeding with the commit.
- **Browser MCP verification must prove behavior**: When manually validating UI with the IDE browser MCP (or any manual browser pass), do not treat “clicked the control” as success. After each interaction that should change state (e.g. `<select>`, toggle, form submit), assert the **observable outcome**: visible text, selected option value (`toHaveValue` for native `<select>`), `aria-*` attributes, or dependent UI that only updates when state is correct. If the UI can be English or Spanish, use flexible matchers (regex or role + partial name) but still assert the concrete post-condition. A control that opens but does not update the model should fail the check.
- **E2E selects and similar controls**: Playwright tests that use `selectOption` (or combobox interaction) MUST assert the **DOM value matches real app behavior**. For **controlled** fields that open a confirmation dialog before committing, the select often **stays on the previous value** until the user confirms; in those cases assert that stale value after the interaction **and** assert `toHaveValue(expected)` after the dialog completes and data settles. For **immediate** commits (no dialog), assert the new value right away and again after any refetch if flaky. Do not rely only on network request hooks.
